SIMPLE: imperialism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imperialism
<hw>Im*pe"ri*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The power or character of an emperor; imperial authority; the
spirit of empire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Roman <qex>imperialism</qex> had divided the world.</q>
<rj><qau>C. H. Pearson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The policy, practice, or advocacy of seeking, or
acquiescing in, the extension of the control, dominion, or empire of a
nation, as by the acquirement of new, esp. distant, territory or
dependencies, or by the closer union of parts more or less independent
of each other for operations of war, copyright, internal commerce, etc.
The practise of building or extending an empire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tide of English opinion began to turn about 1870, and since
then it has run with increasing force in the direction of what is called
<qex>imperialism</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>James Bryce.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperialist</ent>⟦br⟧
